Algorithm¶

The algorithm has two main parameters:

  • Number of points, $p$.
  • Circle radius (distance from the target pixel), $r$.

Next figure show the effect of those parameters, the images shows the points used using different $p$ and $r$ values.

scikit-image algorithm link: https://scikit-image.org/docs/dev/auto_examples/features_detection/plot_local_binary_pattern.html

def overlay_labels(image, lbp, labels):
    mask = np.logical_or.reduce([lbp == each for each in labels])
    return label2rgb(mask, image=image, bg_label=0, alpha=0.5)


def highlight_bars(bars, indexes):
    for i in indexes:
        bars[i].set_facecolor('r')
        

def hist(ax, lbp):
    n_bins = int(lbp.max() + 1)
    return ax.hist(lbp.ravel(), density=True, bins=n_bins, range=(0, n_bins),
                   facecolor='0.5')

In [10]:
# plot histograms of LBP of textures
fig, (ax_img, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=3, figsize=(12, 9))
plt.gray()

titles = ('edge', 'flat', 'corner')
w = width = radius - 1
edge_labels = range(n_points // 2 - w, n_points // 2 + w + 1)
flat_labels = list(range(0, w + 1)) + list(range(n_points - w, n_points + 2))
i_14 = n_points // 4            # 1/4th of the histogram
i_34 = 3 * (n_points // 4)      # 3/4th of the histogram
corner_labels = (list(range(i_14 - w, i_14 + w + 1)) +
                 list(range(i_34 - w, i_34 + w + 1)))

label_sets = (edge_labels, flat_labels, corner_labels)

for ax, labels in zip(ax_img, label_sets):
    ax.imshow(overlay_labels(image, lbp, labels))

for ax, labels, name in zip(ax_hist, label_sets, titles):
    counts, _, bars = hist(ax, lbp)
    highlight_bars(bars, labels)
    ax.set_ylim(top=np.max(counts[:-1]))
    ax.set_xlim(right=n_points + 2)
    ax.set_title(name)

ax_hist[0].set_ylabel('Percentage')
for ax in ax_img:
    ax.axis('off')

Tasks¶

Using the images from the train and test folders, used respectively as train and test data, build an image classifier.

Each image class is specified in its file name. There are three classes: banded, braided i veined.

You can use a linear SVM.

Explain the results.

In [2]:
"""
Extract LBP features from an image.
"""

def extract_features(image_path, radius=3):
    n_points = 8 * radius
    image = cv2.imread(image_path, cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE) # Read in greyscale
    lbp = local_binary_pattern(image, n_points, radius, method="uniform")
    print(f'lbp shape: {lbp.shape}')
    (hist, _) = np.histogram(lbp.ravel(), bins=np.arange(0, n_points + 3), range=(0, n_points + 2))
    
    # Normalize the histogram
    hist = hist.astype("float")
    hist /= (hist.sum() + 1e-7)
    return hist
In [3]:
def prepare_data(folder_path):
    features = []
    labels = []
    for img_path in glob(os.path.join(folder_path, "*.jpg")):
        label = os.path.basename(img_path).split('_')[0]
        print(f'Label of {img_path} is {label}')
        feature_vector = extract_features(img_path)
        features.append(feature_vector)
        labels.append(label)
    return np.array(features), np.array(labels)
    
# Paths --> training and testing folders
train_folder = 'train'
test_folder = 'test'

X_train, y_train = prepare_data(train_folder)
X_test, y_test = prepare_data(test_folder)

Results explanation:¶

In [7]:
predictions = svm.predict(X_test)
conf_mat = confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions)

# Print de confusion matrix
print("Confusion Matrix:")
sns.heatmap(conf_mat, annot=True, fmt='g', cmap='Blues', xticklabels=svm.classes_, yticklabels=svm.classes_)
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
plt.ylabel('True Class')
plt.xlabel('Predicted Class')
plt.show()

print('Accuracy:', accuracy_score(y_test, predictions))

Confusion Matrix:

Accuracy: 0.5

The confusion matrix you have provided shows that the SVM classifier you have trained has predicted all test instances as belonging to the 'banded' class. Here is a breakdown of what the confusion matrix reveals the next:

  • True Positives (TP): The classifier has correctly predicted 2 instances of the 'banded' class.
  • False Negatives (FN): The classifier has failed to correctly predict any instances of the 'braided' and 'veined' classes. Instead, it has misclassified these instances as 'banded'. This is indicated in the first column where there should have been 0 for 'banded', but instead there is 1 for 'braided' and 1 for 'veined'.

Moreover, the accuracy of 0.5 means that, out of all test instances, only 50% were classified correctly. In this case, 2 out of 4 instances were classified correctly as 'banded', and the other 2 were misclassifications of the other classes.

Why this is happening?¶

The training set contains more instances of the 'banded' class compared to 'braided' and 'veined', which may cause the classifier to be biased towards predicting 'banded' due to an imbalanced training data. Moreover, the small training set size could lead to the model overfitting to the 'banded' class, which was the majority in training. But, what can metrics say?

      veined       0.00      0.00      0.00         1

    accuracy                           0.50         4
   macro avg       0.17      0.33      0.22         4
weighted avg       0.25      0.50      0.33         4

As it can see, a classification report about our classifier is not a helpfull idea, their significance is limited due to several factors as the small dataset, where only 4 images are in the test set, each instance heavily influences the overall metrics. Moreover, te lack of predictive power for minority classes, the precision and recall for 'braided' and 'veined' are 0, indicating the model failed to predict any instances of these classes correctly, due to the model has not learned features that are discriminative for these classes.
